Engineering Mathematics - a. Programming and Data Structures Programming in C: functions, structures, memory management, recursion, arrays, stacks, queues, linked lists, trees, binary search trees, binary heaps, graphs. Bond Length The distance between the nuclei of the two atoms joined by the bond is called the bond length. The length of a covalent bond between two given atoms depends on whether it is a sigma bond or combination of a sigma and œÄ - bond or œÄ - bonds, i.e., it is a single, double or triple bond. It also depends on the type of hybridization and the resonance. The bond length is less for a double bond than a single bond and less again for a triple bond than a double bond. Single bond ( œÉ - bond) > Double bond (one œÉ - and one œÄ - bond) (one œÉ - and two œÄ - bonds) The bond length of the sigma bond in different types of hybridization follows the following order : œÉ - bond ( s p 3 ) > œÉ - bond ( s p 2 ) > œÉ - bond ( s p ) Bond length between two given atoms is approximately constant in different molecules depending upon the above conditions unless it is not affected by inductive effect and mesomerism. The bond length is expressed in angstrom units ( AÃä ) . The bond lengths are measured by X - ray crystallography and by microwave spectroscopy. For most of the bonds the values are 1 to 2 AÃä . It may be noted that the values of bond lengths are subject to small changes, depending on the structural environment of the bond and the experimental method used to measure it.
